---
name: Apicius
period: 4th century
---


*Apicius* is the title we give to the only substantially complete Roman cookbook to survive, and in fact the only cookbook of any kind to survive from anywhere in the world before the 9th century. We know very little about it. The name comes from Marcus Gavius Apicius, a gourmet of the early 1st century who lived under Tiberius and was famous in his own time for luxurious living and an obsession with food. According to Seneca, he spent around 100 million sesterces on his kitchen, and when he found himself with only 10 million left—a large fortune still—he poisoned himself rather than endure a life of lesser meals.

Apicius did not write the work that bears his name. It seems doubtful he wrote any recipe book, and this one least of all: it contains dishes named for emperors who reigned long after his death. Instead his name attached first to particular dishes he devised or that were devised in his household, then to a whole style of luxury cooking, and eventually became a byword for lavish dining generally. Something similar happened with the collection [Vinidarius](/recipes/vinidarius/) excerpted, which was also called "Apicius": it resembles the surviving *Apicius* in style, but the recipes themselves do not overlap, so it was a different collection travelling under the same name.

The surviving *Apicius* is a composite. The recipes are written in wildly different registers, from bare lists of ingredients to elaborate step-by-step preparations, in Latin that ranges from competent to badly broken. It was clearly never the work of a single author: recipes repeat, some sit in the wrong place, and a few appear to have been translated from Greek. The compilation was probably assembled around the 4th century, judging by its language, but some recipes are much older—several call for silphium, which was extinct by the reign of Nero—and my guess is that the bulk date to somewhere around the 2nd century, since the named dishes tend to reference figures of the 1st and 2nd centuries. It runs to ten books and roughly 450 recipes.

The Latin text comes from the Grocock and Grainger edition of *Apicius* (*A Critical Edition with an Introduction and English Translation*, Prospect Books, 2006), which is the best source for more information on the text and contains an English translation; the ones below are mine.
